nodes.text: Suan Desouza : Could I just make two points.
Suan Desouza : Firstly, Israel have been deploying out the Pfizer vaccine.
firstly, Israel have been deploying out the Pfizer vaccine
Suan Desouza : they managed to roll out a million vaccines in 12 days
Israel managed to roll out a million vaccines in 12 days
Suan Desouza : The second point, you mentioned about the 12-week gap between the first and second dose for Pfizer.
the second point, you mentioned about the 12-week gap between the first and second dose for Pfizer

Suan Desouza : The World Health Organisation yesterday were very clear that they reckoned that -- well, they stated that it should be between 21 and 28 days maximum gap between the first and second dose and, in exceptional circumstances, up to 6 weeks.

the World Health Organisation yesterday were very clear that they stated that it should be between 21 and 28 days maximum gap between the first and second dose and, in exceptional circumstances, up to 6 weeks
Suan Desouza :  I’ve had five friends of mine contacting me today specifically worried about why we are not following the World Health Organisation rules and advice and Pfizer’s advice as well.
Suan Desouza have had five friends of mine contacting me today specifically worried about why we are not following the World Health Organisation rules and advice and Pfizer’s advice as well
Suan Desouza : Shall I come to Mark on that.
Fiona Bruce : In terms of the question, could we move faster
in terms of the question, we could or couldn't move faster with the vaccine rollout
Nadhim Zahawi : The limitation was actually the vaccine delivery
the limitation of the vaccine rollout was actually the vaccine delivery

Nadhim Zahawi : with Pfizer/BioNTech we had to hold back 50 percent until the regulator, the MHRA and the Joint Committee on Vaccination and Immunisation and the chief medical officers said we could go to a 12-week interval between doses instead of the three-week interval

with Pfizer/BioNTech we had to hold back 50 percent until the regulator, the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency and the Joint Committee on Vaccination and Immunisation and the chief medical officers said we could go to a 12-week interval between doses instead of the three-week interval
Nadhim Zahawi : this week, as of Monday, we got 530,000 doses of the AstraZeneca Oxford vaccine
this week, as of Monday, we got 530,000 doses of the AstraZeneca Oxford vaccine
Nadhim Zahawi : you are talking about 13 plus million people who will be the vaccine
you are talking about 13 plus million people who will be vaccinated
Fiona Bruce : It is just under 14 million, isn’t it
Susan Desouza : Both Pfizer and AstraZeneca insist there is no shortage of vaccines
both Pfizer and AstraZeneca insist there is no shortage of vaccines
Susan Desouza : If Israel can manage 16,000 vaccinations every day, why can’t we do better
if Israel can manage 16,000 vaccinations every day, why can’t we do better
Nadhim Zahawi : We started on 8 December with the Pfizer/BioNTech vaccine
we started on 8 December with the Pfizer/BioNTech vaccine
Nadhim Zahawi : which we were focussing on which is the over 80s
we were focussing on the most vulnerable which is the over 80s
Nadhim Zahawi : We have now vaccinated 1 quarter, 25 percent of people who are over 80
we have now vaccinated 1 quarter, 25 percent of people who are over 80
Nadhim Zahawi : In two weeks’ time they will have that protection when the vaccine begins to really take effect
in two weeks’ time they will have that protection when the vaccine begins to really take effect
Fiona Bruce : Rachel, you’re on the frontline in terms of dealing with patients.
Rachel Clarke : Not only a month after we started rolling out the Pfizer vaccine are three-quarters of the over 80s unvaccinated
not only a month after we started rolling out the Pfizer vaccine are three-quarters of the over 80s unvaccinated

Rachel Clarke : There are paramedics, nurses, healthcare assistants, doctors, NHS and care workers in their thousands who every day are going into an environment in which the air is thick with COVID and we are completely unvaccinated

there are paramedics, nurses, healthcare assistants, doctors, NHS and care workers in their thousands who every day are going into an environment in which the air is thick with COVID and we are completely unvaccinated
Rachel Clarke :  it’s not our fault, it’s a supply issue
inadequat PPE and beeing unvaccinated is not our fault, it’s a supply issue
Rachel Clarke : Here we are again, second time round, completely exposed to a virus that has already killed over 650 frontline NHS and care staff
here we are again, second time round, completely exposed to a virus that has already killed over 650 frontline NHS and care staff
Rachel Clarke : So this couldn’t be more pertinent
Humphrey Cobbold : Annaliese is right in terms of the progress that needs to happen now
Humphrey Cobbold : It is a logistics and planning exercise
the vaccine roll-out is a logistics and planning exercise
Humphrey Cobbold : I think you’ll find, Nadhim, there is a willingness across the population and across businesses to do whatever you need, whatever is required to accelerate and deliver this vaccine
there is a willingness across the population and across businesses to do whatever you need, whatever is required to accelerate and deliver this vaccine
Humphrey Cobbold : There’s enough people, enough goodwill in this country to make that happen
there is enough people, enough goodwill in this country to make 4 million vaccines a week happen
Humphrey Cobbold : I’m confident of that
Fiona Bruce : This presumably is taking a toll on you
Rachel Clarke : We have lost more than the entire Australian death toll in 24-hours
we have lost more than the entire Australian death toll in 24-hours
Rachel Clarke : Conditions in hospitals are unimaginable
conditions in hospitals are unimaginable
Rachel Clarke : We have ambulances queuing up outside
we have ambulances queuing up outside
Rachel Clarke : patients we can’t get them out of the ambulances into hospitals
we cannot get patients out of the ambulances into hospitals
Rachel Clarke :  Tonight I had messages from a doctor in London to tell me that police cars are delivering critically ill COVID patients into his hospital in London
tonight Rachel Clarke had messages from a doctor in London to tell me that police cars are delivering critically ill COVID patients into his hospital in London
Mark Walport : I’m afraid the second wave was entirely predictable.
Rachel Clarke : That is how bad things are
Mark Walport is afraid the second wave was entirely predictable
that is how bad things are
Rachel Clarke : SAGE told the government in September to have a circuit breaker
SAGE told the government in September to have a circuit breaker
Rachel Clarke : They told the government before Christmas: You have to lock down
SAGE told the government before Christmas that they have to lock down
Fiona Bruce : you called for tougher measures back in September.
SAGE called for tougher measures back in September
Mark Walport : We printed the evidence to the government that there was likely to be a second wave.
Rachel Clarke : And that is reprehensible
SAGE printed the evidence to the government that there was likely to be a second wave
Mark Walport : Obviously the government is looking at the direct harms we are talking about now, also the economic damage, the loss to education, all these other things.
obviously the government is looking at the direct harms we are talking about now, also the economic damage, the loss to education, all these other things
Mark Walport : It is for them to balance.
it is for the government to balance the direct harms
Mark Walport :  This really is an absolutely critical moment where the numbers are higher than they were in the first wave in almost everything.
this really is an absolutely critical moment where the numbers are higher than they were in the first wave in almost everything
Mark Walport : People have to really, really socially distance.
Rachel Clarke : Can I follow on from that point about disappointment
Rachel Clarke : On Monday he looked the nation in the eye and said his target, which we would deliver is 13.9 million vaccines by the middle of February
on Monday Boris Johnson looked the nation in the eye and said his target, which we would deliver is 13.9 million vaccines by the middle of February
Nadhim Zahawi : I’m on record as saying we will deliver that
Nadhim Zahawi is on record as saying we will deliver 13.9 million vaccines by the middle of February
Nadhim Zahawi : We will absolutely deliver for the first four cohorts by mid February
we will absolutely deliver for the first four cohorts by mid February
Fiona Bruce : I appreciate that but there are other questions our audience want to put and I want to hear them
Chris Auron : We have entered a third lockdown
Chris Auron : How many more lives were lost before the government decided to call this lockdown
the number of lives that were lost before the government decided to call the third lockdown is xxx
Chris Auron : we’ve got 30,000 people in intensive care units fighting for their lives
we’ve got 30,000 people in intensive care units fighting for their lives
Chris Auron : I wouldn’t want anybody to go through what I’m going through as a family
Chris Auron wouldn’t want anybody to go through the grief he is going through as a family after losing his mother
Chris Auron : 76,000 other families out there are going through the same
Nadhim Zahawi : we’ve done 1.3 million vaccinations, a quarter of the over 80s I mentioned
we’ve done 1.3 million vaccinations, a quarter of the over 80-year-olds Zahawi mentioned earlier
Nadhim Zahawi : Between 4 and 11 January you are going to see another step-up
between 4th and 11th of January you are going to see another step-up
Nadhim Zahawi : because the NHS plan and the rollout that has been delivered in a methodical way
the NHS plan and the rollout has been delivered in a methodical way
Nadhim Zahawi : Our target is to get to the 13.89 million
our target is to get to the 13.89 million
Nadhim Zahawi : the data release is tomorrow and then from next week every single day the prime minister wants to, every day, say the data of everybody we vaccinated
the data release of the vaccinated people is tomorrow and then from next week every single day the prime minister wants to say the data of everybody we vaccinated
Mark Walport : Clearly we’re in a race between getting people vaccinated and the new more transmissible variant
clearly we’re in a race between getting people vaccinated and the new more transmissible variant
Mark Walport : The reality is that the supply of vaccine is limited at the moment
the reality is that the supply of vaccine is limited at the moment
Mark Walport : So long as people get the second dose, then it isn’t critical whether you get it quickly or a bit later in terms of getting the secondary immune response
so long as people get the second dose, it isn’t critical whether you get it quickly or a bit later in terms of getting the secondary immune response
Mark Walport : not perfect but probably the right thing to do under the circumstances where the vaccine is limited
Fiona Bruce : you are, working in intensive care at the moment
Bethany Unknown : a lot of what Rachel said resonates
Bethany Unknown : It is awful
what Rachel Clarke said is awful
Bethany Unknown :  if we had gone into lockdown earlier
Fiona Bruce : they only called for full lockdown a few days ago
they only called for full lockdown a few days ago
Anneliese Dodds : This claim that somehow you can trade off the economy against public health, I’m afraid we’ve seen in spades in this country that simply doesn’t work
Anneliese Dodds : In terms of the latest lockdown, yes, we did call for a full lockdown before the government announced it
in terms of the latest lockdown, we did call for a full lockdown before the government announced it
Anneliese Dodds : before Christmas, I have to say, we were very concerned about the situation then
before Christmas, Anneliese Dodds has to say, we were very concerned about the situation then
Anneliese Dodds : we’re probably seeing, sadly, because of the lag in this disease then coming through into hospitals
we’re probably seeing, sadly, because of the lag in this disease then coming through into hospitals
Anneliese Dodds : We can’t have this what feels like a constant lag between evidence coming through and then action
we can’t have this what feels like a constant lag between evidence coming through and then action
Colette Unknown : we’ve a lot of logistical issues
we’ve a lot of logistical issues in regard to Covid-19 vaccines
George Unknown : Because its -- you go to the supermarket, things like that, there’s people refusing to wear masks and other people just literally disrespecting what everybody is trying to do
when you go to the supermarket, there are people refusing to wear masks and other people just literally disrespecting what everybody is trying to do
Colette Unknown : We have the problem of supply
we have the problem of supply with Covid-19 vaccines
George Unknown : It is really, really frustrating
Fiona Bruce : How quickly can Rachel get her vaccine
Fiona Bruce : That’s why I’m asking about community pharmacies
that’s why Fiona Bruce is asking about community pharmacies
Nadhim Zahawi : When you go through cohorts 1 to 4, our absolute target is to do that by mid February
when you go through cohorts 1 to 4, our absolute target is to do that by mid February
Anneliese Dodds : this is a race against time, as Mark just sated
Nadhim Zahawi : By mid-February I guarantee you everybody will have been offered a vaccine
getting the Covid-19 vaccines out is a race against time, as Mark Walport just stated
by mid-February Nadhim Zahawi guarantees that everybody will have been offered a COVID-19 vaccine
Rachel Clarke : There are 30,000 patients with COVID in our hospitals right now
there are 30,000 patients with COVID-19 in UK hospitals right now
Anneliese Dodds : We need to be moving forward much more quickly
we need to be moving forward much more quickly
Mark Walport : The disappointment is there wasn’t the manufacture at risk and testing of sufficient quantity so it was there ready to be rolled out
Anneliese Dodds : There’s a huge amount of goodwill
there’s a huge amount of goodwill
Anneliese Dodds : People want to help in this national effort to get as many people as possible vaccinated
people want to help in this national effort to get as many people as possible vaccinated
Audience Unknown : She mentioned that 650 people, healthcare workers have died as a result of COVID
650 healthcare workers have died as a result of COVID
Audience Unknown : I really want to know why that is
Anneliese Dodds : We can’t have a repeat of those issues now when we’re rolling out the vaccine
Fiona Bruce : The community pharmacy, there are 11,000 of them, have been saying today they typically do the flu jab vaccine
Nadhim Zahawi : they are the most vulnerable people to this virus, the over 80s
the over 80s are the most vulnerable people to this virus
Nadhim Zahawi : 115 will come on line on the 11th of this month
115 will come on line on the 11th of this month
Nadhim Zahawi : we are adding on national vaccination centres that will come online in details, and the community pharmacies which you talk about
we are adding on national vaccination centres that will come online in details, and the community pharmacies which you talk about
Fiona Bruce : What would you do, Humphrey
Humphrey Cobbold : I would close all the other areas of retail that are not truly essential
Humphrey Cobbold would close all the other areas of retail that are not truly essential
Humphrey Cobbold : there’s a little bit of lackness in attitude around that
there’s a little bit of lackness in attitude around the calls to stay at home
Nadhim Zahawi : when the PM got the data on 18 December, we went into tier 4, or the 19th, within a day we went into tier 4
when the PM got the data on 18 December, we went into tier 4, or the 19th, within a day we went into tier 4
Nadhim Zahawi : As this new variant has taken hold we’ve had to go into this much more severe national lockdown
as this new variant has taken hold we’ve had to go into this much more severe national lockdown
Nadhim Zahawi : the idea that somehow, you know, we hadn’t been responding to how the virus was behaving
Fiona Bruce : Mark, you’re nodding away to that
Mark Walport : this new variant has made things much, much more difficult
this new COVID variant has made things much, much more difficult

Mark Walport : the challenge has been, really, the policy compromises between managing the economy, work, education, and managing the coronavirus has meant actually damage to neither has been minimised as much as it could have been.

the challenge has been that the policy compromises between managing the economy, work, education, and managing the coronavirus has meant actually damage to neither has been minimised as much as it could have been
Fiona Bruce : one of the key reasons why lockdown occurs is to protect the NHS
one of the key reasons why lockdown occurs is to protect the NHS
Dave Unknown : we just keep constantly looking backwards and not forwards.
James   : The economy is in tatters
the economy is in tatters
James   : We’re not getting any of the balancing act right at all
Dave Unknown : We need to be looking forward, not backward
We need to be looking forward, not backward
Humphrey Cobbold : I run a commercial business, obviously, that relies on being opened and not locked down.
Humphrey Cobbold : But I think Mark hit the nail on the head when he said that, you know, this new variant really changed the game.
Humphrey Cobbold thinks Mark hit the nail on the head when he said this new variant really changed the game
Humphrey Cobbold : I think we need to move -- needed to move quicker to lockdown than we did move.
Humphrey Cobbold thinks we need to move quicker to lockdown than we did move
Humphrey Cobbold : Even now I would challenge us to say shouldn’t we be locked down even further.
even now Humphrey Cobbold would challenge us to say we should be locked down even further
Humphrey Cobbold : There are substantial parts of retail and other areas that still open
there are substantial parts of retail and other areas that still open
Humphrey Cobbold : we have talked about it at some length,
Susan Desouza : but by the second week I recognised I should go for lunch and dinner
Chris Auron : we still didn’t lock down even though the statistics were there before Christmas
we still didn’t lock down even though the statistics were there before Christmas
Chris Auron : we can all seem to agree that we probably should have locked down earlier
Chris Auron : maybe we need a more severe lockdown
maybe we need a more severe lockdown
Fiona Bruce : We have 30,000 in hospital
Rachel Clarke : I wouldn’t wish what she and what you as a family have gone through to anybody
Rachel Clarke wouldn’t wish what his mum and what you as a family have gone through to anybody
Rachel Clarke : it divides British society into two tiers
Unknown Speaker : Do you think the government was right to wait until the first day of school to announce school closures
the government was or was not right to wait until the first day of school to announce school closures
Humphrey Cobbold : We are grateful for it, every little helps
we are grateful for it, every little helps
Fiona Bruce : The shadow education said they wanted the schools to stay open, then in the afternoon they wanted them closed
the shadow education said the Labour Party wanted the schools to stay open, then in the afternoon they wanted them closed
Humphrey Cobbold : there’s much more we can do
there’s much more we can do
Anneliese Dodds : this period has been really tough for so many families and we need a much stronger response from government than what we’ve seen so far
Humphrey Cobbold : We won’t be able to reflate the economy and build the economy back
we won’t be able to reflate the economy and build the economy back
Humphrey Cobbold : It is going to be so important to provide the services we want and the jobs in the future that we all want in the future from this
Josh Unknown : he won’t trust teachers to decide when they shouldn’t be in school
Josh Unknown : he’s the worst that Britain has ever seen
Gavin Williamson is the worst education minister that Britain has ever seen
James Unknown : this new variant was a surprise
this new variant of COVID was a surprise
James Unknown : The second wave wasn’t
the second wave of COVID wasn’t a surprise
James Unknown : To get kids in school one day, put teachers at risk, families at risk, then to pull them out the next
to get kids in school one day, put teachers at risk, families at risk, then to pull them out the next
James Unknown : Gavin Williams is pathetic
Gavin Williamson is pathetic
Amanda King : I’m actually one of the few individuals who’s a sole trader who actually runs what is classed as an essential business on the high street
Fiona Bruce : You weren’t criticising those grants to the supermarkets at the time
Anneliese Dodds : We have said that we think support should be better targeted
we have said that we think support should be better targeted
Anneliese Dodds : Now the point is, again going back to what Dave said before, it is not dwelling on the past it is looking to the future
it is not dwelling on the past it is looking to the future
Amanda King : There is no support for us
there is no support for us
Amanda King : We fall, yet again, through the gaps and we don’t get anything
we fall, yet again, through the gaps and we don’t get anything
Nadhim Zahawi : We have this new variant which, clearly, is spiking
we have this new variant of Covid-19 which, clearly, is spiking
Nadhim Zahawi : the lockdown has come in
the lockdown has come in
Nadhim Zahawi : by the middle of February, those first four categories, the most vulnerable four categories
by the middle of February, those first four categories, the most vulnerable four categories
Fiona Bruce :  There’s a rise of the eyebrows from Mark
Mark Walport : We just have to look at the numbers rocketing up at the moment
we just have to look at the numbers rocketing up at the moment
Mark Walport : what Humphrey says makes a lot of sense
Fiona Bruce : A tighter lockdown
a tighter lockdown or not
Fiona Bruce : The question is about school closures
Fiona Bruce : Was the government right to wait until the first day of term to announce the closures
the government was or was not right to wait until the first day of term to announce the school closures
Nicola Unknown : I would like to agree with what’s been said about Gavin Williams
Fiona Bruce : clearly there has been a lot of criticism of Gavin Williams
clearly there has been a lot of criticism of Gavin Williams
Fiona Bruce : by the end of Monday saying, hang on, we’re going to completely change our mind, no, they’re not safe after all
no, schools are not safe after all
Andrea Unknown : So I’m also self-employed and I’ve also fallen through the gaps completely.
Andrea is also self-employed and she has also fallen through the gaps completely
Anneliese Dodds : so much of that money has not been targeted effectively.
so much of 280 billion pounds has not been targeted effectively
Anneliese Dodds : Some of the excluded groups.
Nadhim Zahawi : the local authorities, and I agree with Colette, they should be making those grants land into businesses
Fiona Bruce : Colette, you are nodding vigorously to that
Collette   :  We get the chancellor who goes on TV, with the offer of help, which is amazing
we get the chancellor who goes on TV, with the offer of help, which is amazing
Collette   : A loft of these counsels are holding on to the money and it is not coming down to small businesses
a loft of these counsels are holding on to the money and it is not coming down to small businesses
Humphrey Cobbold: I see a really long COVID problem for employment when we are part of solution, not the problem
James Allcock : While the packages are better than nothing, they’re not enough
while the packages from the chancellor are better than nothing, they’re not enough
Nadhim Zahawi : My target is mid February for the first cohort
Nadhim Zahawi's target is mid February for the first cohort of the nine categories
Nadhim Zahawi : We are going to be publishing daily numbers so the nation can see where we’re at as we increase
the UK government are going to be publishing daily numbers so the nation can see where they are at as they increase vaccination
